            <p></p><h1>Ring Size Conversion Chart</h1>
<p>These are some common ring sizes as well as their corresponding millimet=
er and inch measurements. <br> There are a couple of ways to measure what r=
ing size you need for your purposes. If you already know your ring size, or=
 have a ring that fits, you can use a <a href=3D"https://artbeads.com/ring-=
mandrel/">ring mandrel</a>. This tool has the ring sizes listed on it. Slid=
e the ring onto the tool and wherever it rests should list the correct ring=
 size. You can also use the ring mandrel to make wire-wrapped wrings in the=
 correct size. If you don't have a ring mandrel and don't know your ring si=
ze, you can use a strip of paper or string around the desired finger. Wrap =
it snugly and comfortably around the finger and mark where the ends meet. F=
latten your paper or string and measure it against a ruler. You can then co=
nvert that measurement to determine your ring size using the table below.</=
p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Ring Size Measurements</strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
